slides.title: Mapping the actors engaged in post-Snowden controversies
slides.text:
On June 5th, 2013, The Guardian ran the first article based on the trove of secret documents disclosed by whistleblower Edward Snowden. This release marked the beginning of a sustained effort by investigative journalists, computer security experts, human rights advocates and many other actors to document the Internet surveillance practices of the world's most powerful intelligence agencies.

A global controversy quickly unleashed, and then developed in a myriad of both global and national debates. In what follows, we present a corpus of websites representing actor networks engaged in global post-Snowden controversies, collected by using the Web-curation tool Hyphe (http://hyphe.medialab.sciences-po.fr/).

slides.title: A word on methodology
slides.text:
We started from a couple dozens of websites of NGOs advocating surveillance reform as well as key news articles on the Snowden files. To curate websites , if we did not have prior knowledge of the actor's engagement in (or at least a strong connection to) post-Snowden controversies, we would run a quick search to see if the website mentioned terms like “Snowden” or “Internet surveillance”. If results came in for that query, we would add the “web entity” to the corpus.

Of course, this only gives a partial account of the really-existing controversy: In many instances, it develops in audiovisual media, tweets, parliamentary reports, “real life” events and through many other mediums, all of which cannot be tracked by simply following hyperlinks between public-facing websites. 

Another word of caution: Although global in nature, the main post-Snowden controversy remains closely tied to the transatlantic space, and more specifically to the US. One good reason for that is that the National Security Agency is the main focus of these disclosures. Another is that English is the primary language in which this global controversy unfolds. The result is that most of the close to 370 websites presented here are either US or British, downplaying the significance of the national controversies developing in countries like Germany, Brazil, France or the Netherlands, among others.

slides.title: Applying a taxonomy
slides.text:
This mapping exercise was conducted at a preliminary stage of ongoing research projects. Its main goal was to identify the range and diversity of actors engaged in global post-Snowden controversies.

The Web corpus helped develop this taxonomy. It is comprised of six top-level categories (institutions, media, academia, hackers & engineers, NGOs, industry), each broken down in several subsets (as you will see, because of software limitations, only the ten most important subcategories can be coloured). 

This presentation is a basic walk-through in this taxonomy and concludes by presenting the next steps of our research. As you explore these categories and subcategories, remember that that the boundaries between between them can be porous.

To activate the taxonomy, click on "Legend" in the bottom-left corner of the graph area. For each of the slides, you can zoom in and out, and click-and-drag to explore the network and its actors.

slides.title: A. MEDIA
slides.text: Media occupy an important place in the network by meditating the controversy for a wide audience as well as interfacing various subnetworks of actors representing smaller, alternative public spheres.

slides.title: A.1 International and national mainstream media
slides.text:
International mainstream media like The Guardian, The Washington Post or the German Der Spiegel obtained direct access to the Snowden files. They played a key role in kickstarting the controversy by analyzing the documents provided by Edward Snowden, often in cooperation with computer experts.

As the controversy unfolded, mainstream media relayed claims and counterclaims by various actors engaged in post-Snowden controversies, putting the issue of intelligence reform at the forefront of the public agenda.

In this category, we also find conservative outlets like Fox News who have helped US national security hawks frame Snowden as a traitor.

slides.title: A.2 Alternative media
slides.text: A few alternative media sources also came up in the results. Some, like DemocracyNow, have strong connections with human rights and other activist causes. They have been an important players to locate the fight against large-scale surveillance as another manifestation of the abuses of the “national security state”.

slides.title: A.3  Whistleblowing platform
slides.text: Under this category, we find media organizations that are also at the crossroad of journalism and advocacy. WikiLeaks, for instance, played a role in advocating for Edward Snowden's whistleblower status and, along with others, organizing his legal representation. At the same time, the organization founded by Julian Assange has been fueling post-Snowden controversy of its own, for instance through documents allegedly coming from another source and pointing to the espionage of French, German and Brazilian governments in mid-2015.

slides.title: A.4 Specialized media
slides.text:
Specialized media, addressing niche audiences, help fuel the controversy according to the various interests, focus or politics of the various communities engaged in the controversy.

Under the terms “Internet politics”, we refer to publications focusing on the socio-political aspects of the Internet. They include Wired, Boing Boing or Global Voices. Their audience includes in particualr people in digital rights circles.

The repercussions of the Snowden disclosures for computer security have led media specialized in this “tech and cybersecurity” (e.g. Techworld or CircleID) to take part in the controversy, helping feed the conversation about how to better protect the technical foundations of the Internet against computer intrusion and exploitation by intelligence agencies.

Finally, another subset of specialized media are those publications focusing of “defense and security” matters, like Security Affairs, Foreign Policy or specialized blogs like Electrospaces. For some of them with close ties to the US military (e.g. Breaking Defense), they have tended to adopt a different framing of the controversy, focusing on how the controversy tends to limit the room for maneuver enjoyed by intelligence agencies.

slides.title: B. NGOs
slides.text: NGOs have been a key player of the Snowden disclosures, using these documents and their analysis to campaign against large-scale surveillance.

slides.title: B.1 Human Rights NGOs
slides.text: Thanks to their expertise in dealing with the illiberal practices developing in liberal regimes after 9/11, international and national human rights NGO like Amnesty, Human Rights Watch and others, have rapidly seized on the Snowden disclosures to campaign against large-scale surveillance.

slides.title: B.2 Digital Rights NGOs
slides.text: Digital Rights NGOs, specialized in the protection of human rights in the digital environment, are usually smaller organizations connecting the human rights field and that of politicized hackers. For the less structured ones, the Snowden disclosures have led them to broker new connections with the usually older and larger human rights NGOs. They include the Electronic Frontier Foundation, EDRi, ACCESS NOW, the Open Rights Groups, Bits of Freedom, Netzpolitik and La Quadrature du Net. The coalitions and campaign websites of these NGOs are also categorized in this subgroup.

slides.title: B.3 Privacy & Freedom of expression NGOs
slides.text:
In these sub-categories, we find advocacy groups that have developed a particular expertise in the wider field of surveillance (both offline and online, like Privacy International) as well as organizations specialized in the defense freedom of expression.
 
Journalists organizations, for instance, have played an important role in enlarging the common understanding of privacy rights, by showing the direct detrimental impact of surveillance on the confidentiality of sources. They have also mobilized in defense of whistleblowers rights or that of the journalists involved in publishing the Snowden disclosures, for instance to denounced the detention of Glen Greenwald's partner David Miranda by the British police under the Terrorism Act 2000 in August 2013, seizing a hard drive said to be containing sensitive documents relevant to the Greenwald's reporting.

slides.title: B.4 Lawyers
slides.text: Lawyers organizations are also an important group for post-Snowden, carrying on strategic litigation against surveillance and also showing how unchecked surveillance undermined basic defense rights. They include the Council of Bars and Law Societies of Europe, the law office Digital Defenders or Privacy not PRISM, the name of a litigation campaign before the European Court of Human Rights, launched by NGOs Big Brother Watch, Open Rights Group, English PEN against the UK government's surveillance programs.

slides.title: B.5 Artists and filmakers
slides.text:
Although very few of them came up in the Web-corpus, artists and filmakers are an important group of actors. Films like Laura Poitras' “Citizen Four” helped reach wider audiences than those usually affected by the controversy. 

In the art world, so-called “surveillance art” has been getting traction thanks to the Snowden disclosures.

slides.title: C. ENGINEERS & HACKERS
slides.text: Engineers and hackers are the social groups that better grasp the technical intricacies of the modern-day surveillance. They have helped other actors to make sense of the Snowden documents while engaging in a sustained effort aimed at improving computer security.

slides.title: C.1 Technical counter-measures providers
slides.text: Technical counter-measures refer to alternative communications tools aimed at better respect the fundamental rights of users, increasing the cost of surveillance through decentralized architectures and/or the use of cryptography. They are developed by small independent companies or non-profit collectives who typically display a “hacktivists” ethos, with the aim of democratizing the resort to such alternative tools. They include the TOR projects, the operating system TAILS or small companies like Open Whisper Systems (which develops the smartphone application Signal).

slides.title: C.2 Engineering professionals, cybersecurity experts & Internet governance fora
slides.text: Other important subcategories with a strong technical capital include groups which play an important role in developing commonly used technologies. They include engineering professional groups (e.g. IEEE), cybersecurity experts (like CERTs) and Internet governance fora (in charge of developing or promoting Internet standards IETF or ISOC). While some of these groups had long warned about the surveillance capabilities of intelligence agencies, others have received the Snowden controversy as a wake-up call and launched new initiatives aimed at boosting computer security.

slides.title: D. INSTITUTIONS
slides.text: Institutions are national and international organizations in charge of defining, implementing and/or enforcing public policies and regulations. With respect to post-Snowden controversy, they appear as a rather fragmented category.

slides.title: D.1 Intelligence agencies
slides.text:
The primary targets of post-Snowden controversies are intelligence and law enforcement agencies: The Snowden disclosures have shed light on the techno-legal apparatus of surveillance that have become deeply embedded in the daily routine of these agencies. 

Only US agencies came out from our web-crawling exercise (one reason might be the fact that they have developed online public relations to an extent that make their websites valuable sources of information, to the contrary of their foreign counterparts).

slides.title: D.2 Data protection authorities and cybersecurity agencies
slides.text: Data protection agencies (e.g. the French CNIL) or cybersecurity agencies (EU's ENISA) joined the debate by providing bringing legal and technical arguments against the forms of surveillance disclosed by Snowden, for instance in the field of cryptography. In that respect, they brought “institutional certification” to the arguments developed by activists.

slides.title: D.3 International human rights organizations
slides.text: International human rights organizations (e.g. the UN, the Council of Europ.) also supported the claims of civil society, issuing commentaries and adopting official documents against threats to privacy and freedom of expression associated with national security. In doing so, they helped create a degree of institutional pluralism, through their ineffectiveness in actually protecting the rule of law also points to the shortcomings of the international human rights system.

slides.title: D.4  Governments, parliaments, courts
slides.text:
The power of public institutions corresponding to the three branches of government (the executive, the legislative and the judiciary branches) makes them the main targets of advocacy efforts around post-Snowden controversies. Not only those of NGOs and other contentious actors aiming to overturn the current trends towards large-scale surveillance, but also those of security professionals (and others) who seek to have these practices secured at the legal level. These power struggles are currently unfolding in several countries like the UK, the Netherlands and Germany were intelligence reform is currently underway.

As for courts, although they did not show up in the corpus (to the exception of US Courts), their importance is these debates has substantially increased. Indeed, the Snowden disclosures have enable strategic litigation campaigns by civil society, while the wider controversy seem to have given more leeway to judges willing to oppose large-scale surveillance. Several important cases are currently pending before powerful jurisdictions such as the European Court of Human Rights. They now appear as the last institutional resort against suspicionless surveillance.

slides.title: E. INDUSTRY
slides.text: The Snowden disclosures have revealed the intense public-private hybridization in surveillance activities. It has profoundly impacted the power-relationships in this field, decreasing the relative influence of police and intelligence agencies on private firms, while empowering investigative journalists, human rights lawyers, advocacy groups and politicized hackers. But like institutions, industry is a fragmented category.

slides.title: E.1 Global corporations (B2C & B2B) & online service providers
slides.text:
Global corporations refer to multinational firms providing online services, telecom operators and equipment manufacturers. Many of them have been pointed at for their collaboration with intelligence agencies.

Whether their main clientèle is mainly comprised of consumers (B2B) or businesses (B2C) is one of the many factors influencing the public relation strategy in the face of post-Snowden controversies. For instance, B2C Silicon Valley firms like Apple or Google have sought to respond to public concern by boosting the security of their products and engaging with public stand-offs with law enforcement agencies, in an attempt to frame themselves as “privacy-friendly”. B2B companies like CISCO are much less prone to that sort of pressure.

Online service providers refer to companies of significant size --sometimes even multinationals-- providing online services but which have not been reported to collaborate with intelligence agencies.

slides.title: E.2 Cybersecurity providers and surveillance technology providers
slides.text:
Cybersecurity providers --especially European ones (though they did not really come up in the results)-- have often used the Snowden controversy has as a way to develop business arguments based on securitization discourses: Pointing to the danger of surveillance and current gaps in computer security, they market their cybersecurity solutions to businesses and public institutions as a way to regain control over their data. In Europe especially, when they are tied to arguments around “digital sovereignty”, such securitization discourses go hand-in-hand with processes of public-private hybridization in the field of cybersecurity.

Although private firms specialized in national security IT applications (e.g. Booz Allen Hamilton, Snowden's former employer) have been direct targets of this controversy on surveillance, they usually did not come up in the results (to the exception of Fox-It, listed here as a cybersecurity provider, or of large corporations like IBM which have categorized as global corporations). One reason might be that these companies specialized in defense & intelligence technologies usually keep their public communications on these matters to a minimum. 

However, many NGOs (like EFF, Privacy International or RSF) as well as research groups (like the CitizenLab) have helped put the spotlight on these actors providing surveillance solutions to intelligence and other law enforcement agencies. The Hacking Team leaks in the summer of 2015 also contributed to feeding a global debate on the role of these companies in the surveillance arms race.

slides.title: E.3 Trade groups, lobbies & consultancies
slides.text: Trade groups and consultancies are two subcategories that also showed up in the results. In the US, organizations like the Information Technology and Innovation Foundation have engaged in policy debates, pointing to the detrimental impact of the Snowden disclosures for the business of US companies involved in the digital economy (in 2013, ITIF's estimated that concerns about US surveillance could impact foreign markets for computing services and result in losses ranging from $21.5 billion and $35 billion by 2016).

slides.title: F. ACADEMIA
slides.text: The last category of our taxonomy is academia. It is comprised of several subategories: Universities (often US-based), research centers, individual researchers or collectives of researchers providing online commentary or conducting research on issues related to the Snowden-disclosures (Ethan Zuckerman, Bruce Schneier, openDemocracy, Lawfare, CitizenLab, etc.), as well as think-tanks of diverse political leanings (e.g. Pew Internet, Brookings Institution).

slides.title: Next steps
slides.text:
This preliminary research has allowed us to develop a fine-grained typology of the various actors engaged in post-Snowden controversy, at least as it unfolds on the online public sphere.

As we move forward, we will seek to add to this initial mapping more focused datasets taken from particular case-studies (e.g. the map of the mobilization against the French Intelligence Act; the cartography of surveillance solutions providers known to work with intelligence and law enforcement agencies, etc.). In that way, we will be able to move towards a more comprehensive actors network.

Another important task will be to develop a more fine-grained understanding of the positions of the most important of these actors in the public debate on Internet surveillance. To do so, we will be looking at “subcontroversies”, such as the proportionality of technical surveillance measures, the public-private hybridization in surveillance, the transnationalization of surveillance and national security, the oversight of intelligence activities and issues related to civil society's resistance or obedience to modern-day surveillance. National debates on intelligence reform and ongoing trials around surveillance are of particular interest to study how this subcontroversies develop.

slides.title: The End...
slides.text:
By Félix Tréguer (SciencesPo-CERI) with Audrey Baneyx and Benjamin Ooghe (SciencesPo-Medialab).
